om the beginning, existential thought opposed itself to narrowly self-directed academic philosophy and sought to apply itself to the concrete praxis of human life, as well as to related questions of moral philosophy. Although they differ in many ways, the various approaches of particular existential philosophers all center on the concept of human freedom, which Schelling described as the "faculty of good and evil". This faculty stands as the condition of the possibility of any ethical system.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aEthics. 0aExistentialism. 4aFreedom, Heidegger, Martin, Sartre, Jean-Paul. 4aFreiheit. 4aHeidegger, Martin. 4aSartre, Jean-Paul. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Phenomenology.2bisacsh1 aFeger, Hans, eeditor.1 aHackel, Manuela, eeditor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Philosophy 2000 - 2014z9783110636949oZDB-23-GPH08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK GESAMTPAKET / COMPLETE PACKAGE 2013z9783110317350oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PAKET PHILOSOPHIE  2013z9783110317312oZDB-23-DPH0 cprintz978311033102840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9783110331103423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9783110331103.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DGGb2013  aZDB-23-DPHb2013  aZDB-23-GPHc2000d2014